Part 2: The Quarto File

Iâll be using Quarto documents extensively in this course. Quarto is a ânext genâ RMarkdown. (If youâre using the server, quarto is not installed and youâll be using RMarkdown instead). RMarkdown and Quarto are essentially the same, except Quarto has capabilities beyond R (eg Python, Julia, Observable). RMarkdown = R (statistical software) + Markdown (text formatting language). The output is a ânotebookâ style document that interweaves narrative text, code, and graphs.

There are two steps to getting a final output file:

  1. Write the document in RMarkdown
  2. âRenderâ the file to an output format (usually HTML or PDF)

First, download the template LASTNAME-Lab01.qmd file from github. Then either (a) save it in a âStat61â folder on your computer if youâve downloaded R and RStudio (PLEASE IN THE NAME OF ALL THAT IS HOLY DO NOT LEAVE EVERYTHING IN YOUR DOWNLOADS FOLDER) or (b) upload it to the server by navigating to the âfilesâ pane in the lower right corner and clicking the âuploadâ button. Youâll need to rename the file extension to be .rmd

Once you upload the file, you should see it show up in the file system within RStudio. Click on the file to open it in the âeditorâ. Try clicking the ârenderâ or âknitâ button now to make sure everything works. You may have to hit âtry againâ or âallow pop upâ in order for your PDF to appear. If you run into any problems please let me know now.

Density functions and plotting

Pull up the help page for the dnorm function and scroll down to value. For many of the named probability distributions, thereâs a corresponding d (density), p (distribution), and r (random sample) function. Today, weâre going to focus on the d and r functions.

dnorm(x) evaluates the normal pdf at the value x. If weâre aiming to make a density plot, we need to evaluate the pdf at a reasonable range of xâs. The following code (1) creates a vector called x that goes from -4 to 4 in increments of .1, (2) creates a vector called y that evaluates dnorm at all values of x, (3) creates a line plot with x on the x-axis and y on the y-axis.

x = seq(-4, 4, by = .1)
y = dnorm(x)
plot(x, y, type = "l")

If we want to overlay another line with a different distribution, we use the lines function:

y2 = dnorm(x, mean = -1)
plot(x, y, type = "l")
lines(x, y2)

This is great for making quick plots for ourselves, but we will want more professional looking graphs eventually. I like to use the ggplot package for nicer-looking graphs. You need to install/load the tidyverse package before using this functionality.

With ggplot():

  • The first argument is always the dataset.
  • Next, you provide the variables from the dataset to be assigned to aesthetic elements of the plot, e.g.Â the x and the y axes.
  • Finally, you use another layer, separated by a + to specify the geometric object for the plot. Since we want to scatterplot, we use geom_point().

For instance, if you wanted to visualize the scatterplot below using a line graph, you would replace geom_point() with geom_line(). What happens if you comment out the theme_minimal line and the plus sign in the line above it?

library(tidyverse)

normal_dataset = tibble(
  x = x, 
  y = y
)

ggplot(normal_dataset, aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 20)

For more information on customizing ggplots, try out the RStudio Primer.

The following code is also in your lab report. Can you tell what the first 4 lines of code are creating? Try checking ?dbinom, ?c and ?rep, and you can also click on binomial_dataset in the Environment panel to pull up a spreadsheet view of the data. You can run smaller chunks of code, like dbinom(x_range, size = 10, prob = .6), in the console.

x_range = seq(0, 10, by = 1)

binomial_dataset = tibble(
  x2 = c(x_range, x_range),

  )

Defining your own density function

Weâve seen a few examples in class of pdfâs that arenât one of the common ânamed distributionsâ. For example, when we covered MLE we did an exercise where the pdf was given by:

\[f_y(y; \theta) = \frac{1}{\theta^2}y \exp^{-y/\theta}\] To make our own pdf, we define a function in R:

custom_pdf = function(y, theta){
  return(1/(theta^2) * y * exp(-y/theta))
}

and then we can proceed

y_range = seq(0, 50, by = .5)

custom_pdf_dataset = tibble(
  y = c(y_range, y_range), 
  fy = c(custom_pdf(y_range, 1), custom_pdf(y_range, 5)),
  mod = c(rep("theta=1", length(y_range)), rep("theta=5", length(y_range)))
)

ggplot(custom_pdf_dataset, aes(x = y, y = fy, col = mod)) + 
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 20) + 
  labs(
    x = "y",
    y = "f(y)",
    col = "Model"
  )

Sampling

The d functions that weâve used (or created!) so far give us the theoretical density function for a random variable. In this class, weâll often care about the performance of an estimator for different random samples. For example, here are 8 \(N(0,1)\) samples of size 50. None are perfect bell curves - some are flatter, some are more pointy, some are a little skewed, etc.

Code 
set.seed(091323)
normal_samples = tibble(
  x1 = rnorm(50),
  x2 = rnorm(50),
  x3 = rnorm(50),
  x4 = rnorm(50),
  x5 = rnorm(50),
  x6 = rnorm(50),
  x7 = rnorm(50),
  x8 = rnorm(50)
) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "sample", values_to = "x") 

ggplot(normal_samples, aes(x = x)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap(vars(sample), ncol = 4) + 
  theme_minimal()

If we look at the mean of each of our 8 samples, we see that how âcloseâ we are to the true value, 0, depends on the random sample that we have.

Code 
normal_samples %>%
  group_by(sample) %>%
  summarize(
    mean = mean(x)
  )
# A tibble: 8 Ã 2
  sample     mean
  <chr>     <dbl>
1 x1      0.0543 
2 x2      0.0206 
3 x3      0.00269
4 x4     -0.205  
5 x5     -0.112  
6 x6     -0.0483 
7 x7     -0.104  
8 x8     -0.0226

If you click the âcodeâ button above, the simulaton begins with set.seed(091323). This tells R to make the random samples reproducible. Without setting the seed, we would get different samples every time. With the same random seed, we guarantee that weâll all get the same 8 random samples. Whenever you do simulations, itâs good practice to set the seed to guarantee that (a) someone can replicate your analysis, and (b) your interpretation and write-up will âmatchâ the simulation results.
